Or the other way of looking at that is &quot;which classes by design from just turning on autoattack are going to be the people the ubermob turns on and trys to squash?&quot;  That's right,  its the folks that are designed to be doing warrior or warrior+ damage and constantly working to manage their agro. (with bard as the odd man out, and I don't know enough about bst + pet at 60).   Hmmm, DA would be, oh, several hundred times more useful to a monk than just voiddance itself is, so maybe that's a bias in my view... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usenchy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Senchy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blessed Protector</span><br>  Posts: 444<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/3/02 4:52:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15416.topic&index=80>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: no we're not and any of you who say we are are fools!</span><hr size=1> Personally I am against changes/improvement to classes that take the zest out of high end encounters or destroy the role of other classes. (This is a general statement not necessarily to the discussion about getting paladins a 18sec mitigation disc)<br>
<br>
The challange paladins typically face on raids is controlling aggro while using group heals. For example one change I would like to see is reduce the recast time of HWoP. It would not change encounters drastically but avoid watching your group die in very rough aoes while you hope HWoP pops up again. The aggro that the spell generates is enough to curb the power of HWoP<br>
<br>
Coming back to the discussion about a 18-20sec avoidance disc, I am personally against it since it would simplify many fights. In high end raids, the toughest and battle winning challenge is keeping aggro on one tank and keep him alive.<br>
<br>
Here comes the difference between paladins and the classes that already have a 18-20 100% avoidance discs: We can gain aggro almost instantenously compared to the other classes. The same is true for SKs.<br>
<br>
Warriors, monks, rangers, rogues cannot immediately draw aggro from a dragon after the MT died. If they would be able to, then the battle winning need to keep the MT up and aggro controlled would not be required. The fights would get a lot less challenging. <br>
<br>
Currently when the MT dies unplanned, a bunch of folks die until a new tank can be successfully established. This makes the battles challenging and fun. That makes you proud when you can reestablish a new tank through the skill of everyone <br>
<br>
(paladin lay handing newly established tanks to give clerics time to get CH chain going again, druids spot healing, none warriors turning off attack to give warriors a chance to get aggro)<br>
<br>
Now lets give a paladins a 18-20 sec disc. MT dies and paladin in 5 seconds has fully aggro. Maybe 1-2 die till the paladin is up. With a avoidance disc the clerics would have 18-20 seconds to get the CH chain reestablished and the battle would easily be won. That is forever.<br>
<br>
Except for the ranger none of the other def disc classes can do anything to gain aggro faster than by just hoping. The paladin though compared to the ranger can tank Aary and NToV dragons semi well.<br>
<br>
Even if you do not establish a CH chain, each paladin with def disc up will give the raid a free 18-20 second well aggro controlled time to finish a mob. Fights like Klandicar or Sont would become so boring since 5 pals with our uncanny ability to hold aggro could totally negate the need to even heal the MTs.<br>
<br>
Pal 18 sec defensive would take out the zest of the game. <p>Senchy Solariatus <BR>
